annotations:
Cutting tinsel into gold
 And hoping you won’t love me still

‘Cutting tinsel into gold’ as a relationship metaphor is Ellen knowingly looking at things in a very forgiving light. She knows her love isn’t ‘gold’, just an imitation of it, however she chooses to believe that it’s the real thing.

This is why she hopes her lover will stop loving her, because she is not strong enough to leave on her own and will make excuses to paint things in the best possible light.

God called my life a pretty life
 It made me cry

Despite being objectively aware that she isn’t being treated well, Ellen presumably stays with this love interest because they(referred to as God) makes her feel seen.

‘It made me cry’ speaks to the weight of how special it feels to be appreciated and loved by someone, and that isn’t a feeling she is willing to give up.

body.plain: The song is about reflecting on the loss of somebody close, and how that weight can manifest at any time. In this song, the produce aisle of a grocery store.

annotations:
I can’t bear your fingers drumming
 And I’m feeling all the words
 I am feeling all your words
 And the monster in your bones

Palehound feels berated by their mother, with each word, each movement, being something that they need to defend themselves against. The drumming, the words… they all act as weapons of the eating disorder, the “monster.”



Palehound uses “bones” to connect again to the subject of “Feeling Fruit”: thinness as it relates to the psychological damage perpetrated by eating disorders and diet culture altogether. Additionally, how this disease is perpetuated by parents onto their children (with a potential focus on mother-daughter dynamics/expectations of girlhood).

I am in the produce aisle
 And I’m feeling all the fruits
 I am feeling all the fruits
 Every wormhole, every bruise
People can become permanently scarred and damaged – much like the fruits.

When the night is crowded
 I can only see your face
 I can only see your face
 On a stranger’s healthy frame
The loss of this person is consuming her mind – she is longing for them to be alive and healthy again.
’Cause I’m stuck with the weight you gave up
The loved one had likely died from an illness – and lost a lot of weight in the process. She compares this physical weight with the emotional weight of dealing with the loss.

I am at the grocery store
 After weeks of frozen meals
She has been depressed after losing this person and has not been eating healthy or taking care of herself.
